04216nam a2200769Ia 9780271098388DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710983887 a10.1515/97802710983882doi  a(DE-B1597)691431  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL1000002bisacsh1 aHomza, Lu Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Child Witches of Olague /cLu Ann Homza. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMagic in History Sourcebooks00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tMAP 1 Important witch-hunting sites in northeast Spain, 1608–14. Map created by Mike Bechthold -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 Prior Events -- tChapter 2 Father and Son -- tChapter 3 The Echaide Family and the Two Widows -- tChapter 4 Mother and Daughter -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early seventeenth century, thousands of children in Spain’s Navarre region claimed to have been bewitched. The Child Witches of Olague features the legal depositions of self-described child witches as well as their parents and victims. The volume sheds new light on Navarre’s massive witch persecution (1608–14), illuminating the tragic cost of witch hunts and opening a new window onto our understanding of early modern Iberian life. Drawing from Spanish-language sources only recently discovered, Homza translates and annotates three court cases from Olague in 1611 and 1612. Two were defamation trials involving the slur “witch,” and the third was a petition for divorce filed by an accused witch and wife. These cases give readers rare access to the voices of illiterate children in the early modern period. They also speak to the emotions of witch-hunting, with testimony about enraged, terrified parents turning to vigilante justice against neighbors. Together the cases highlight gender norms of the time, the profound honor code of early modern Navarre, and the power of children to alter adult lives. With translations of Inquisition correspondence and printed pamphlets added for context, The Child Witches of Olague offers a portrait of witch-hunting as a horrific, contagious process that fractured communities. This riveting, one-of-a-kind book will appeal to anyone interested in the history of witch hunts, life in early modern Spain, and history as revealed through court testimony.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aRELIGION / Demonology & Satanism.2bisacsh  aAbuse.  aDevil.  aNavarre.  aSpain.  aadolescents.  aarchives.  aauto-de fe.  aboys.  achildren.  adefamation.  ademons.  adivorce.  adomestic violence.  adrowning.  agender.  agirls.  ainquisition.  ainversion.  alawsuits.  alegal systems.  apoverty.  asabbat.  aslander.  astepchildren.  ateenagers.  awitchcraft.  awitches.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271098388?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271098388423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271098388/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles